        <h1 class="pg-title">Februa</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Roman purification rites — sacrifices, naked priests, and ritual whipping</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        The month of February on the Gregorian calendar is named after Roman purification rites. The Latin word <strong>Februa</strong> means "purifications" or "instruments of cleansing," and the entire month was dedicated to ritual cleansing of the city of Rome — most centrally through a festival called <em>Lupercalia</em>, which involved practices Yahuah's people would have recognized immediately as abominations.
      </p>

      <h2>What the Februa Rites Were</h2>

      <p>
        Lupercalia was held every February 15 in ancient Rome. It was an extremely old festival — older than Rome itself by some accounts — associated with the wolf-god Lupercus and the goat-god Faunus. Priests called <em>Luperci</em> sacrificed goats and a dog at a cave on the Palatine Hill (the cave where Romulus and Remus were said to have been suckled by the wolf), then smeared the blood on their foreheads and wiped it off with wool dipped in milk.
      </p>

      <p>
        After the sacrifice, the Luperci stripped naked, cut strips from the goat hides, and ran through the streets of Rome whipping any woman they encountered. Women would deliberately come into the streets and offer their hands or backs to be whipped, because the blow from a Lupercus was believed to ensure fertility and easy childbirth. The whole festival was a fertility-and-purification rite combined — sacrificial blood, ritual nakedness, ceremonial whipping, all packaged together as Rome's annual cleansing.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Latin verb <em>februare</em> meant "to purify by sacrifice." The instruments used in these rites — the strips of goat hide, the blood-soaked wool — were called <em>februa</em>. The month in which the rites were performed became known as <em>Februarius</em>, the month of purification. From that comes the English February.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        The pagan world believed that ritual cleansing required animal blood, ceremonial nakedness, and ritual violence. Yahuah's instructions for cleansing are nothing like this. The blood of bulls and goats in the Levitical system pointed forward to the Messiah, not backward to a wolf-god. The cleansing Yahuah designed was solemn, modest, and ordered — not a streetside whipping festival.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Psalm 51:7</span> — "Purge me with hyssop, and I shall be clean: wash me, and I shall be whiter than snow."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Hebrews 9:13–14</span> — "For if the blood of bulls and of goats, and the ashes of an heifer sprinkling the unclean, sanctifieth to the purifying of the flesh: How much more shall the blood of Messiah… purge your conscience from dead works to serve the living Elohim?"
      </div>

      <p>
        Real purification — the kind Yahuah designed — points to the blood of the Messiah and the inward cleansing of the heart. The Februa rites were a counterfeit. They imitated the form of sacrifice and the language of cleansing, but they served wolf-gods and goat-gods and ended in public nakedness and ritual violence. To name a month after these rites is to name it after the counterfeit.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What month in Yahuah's calendar is February really?"</em> The question is misplaced.
      </p>

      <p>
        Yahuah's months are counted from the new moon. The first month — Aviv — begins when Spica meets the moon at the new moon nearest the spring equinox. Every month after that begins the day after the visible new-moon sliver appears. The months are numbered. <strong>Their start dates do not line up with the Roman months — and they shift slightly from one year to the next.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        What we call "February" on the Roman calendar will overlap with parts of two different months on Yahuah's calendar — and which two depends on the year. To say "February is really Month X" is to commit the same error as "Christ died on Friday." It mixes Babylon's clock with Yahuah's clock, when the two were never meant to translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Most believers have no idea what Lupercalia was. They have heard of "St. Valentine's Day" on February 14 without realizing it was placed there by the Roman church to overwrite the wolf-god fertility festival the day before. The whole month carries the fingerprint of pagan purification rites that Yahuah's people would have fled from on sight.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> His months are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from a Roman whipping festival held in honor of a wolf-god. The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them when a month has begun. The world watches its phone and lets the Februa rites tell it the year is being purified. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        February is the month of the Februa — a wolf-god's purification rite, sacrifice, and public whipping. The cleansing Yahuah's people need comes from the blood of the Messiah, not from naked priests running through Rome.
      </div>

